salford.gov.uk/allotments.htm','Taking on an allotment plot is not all hard work and has a number of benefits. Allotment gardening provides you with the opportunity to grow fresh vegetables, fruit and flowers for you and your family at a low cost. The majority of these sites are designated for growing fruit, vegetables and flowers but there are several sites where the keeping of livestock is permitted. Rents are charged annually and vary according to the type of facilities on site.',NULL,'SalfordCouncil','https://www.facebook.com/SalfordCouncil',1,150,1,1,53.483322,-2.314572,'eng','2013-05-20 12:00:00','2013-05-20 12:00:00',NULL,NULL,'allotment-gardening'),(152,'Unlimited Potential','Marcia Powell','51 Federick Road',NULL,NULL,'Salford','M6 6FP','0161 7430088','info@unlimitedpotential.org.uk','http://www.unlimitedpotential.org.uk','Unlimited Potential provides a range of high-quality, personal services which aim to make a real difference to the lives of people and the communities in which they live. Services include Health Trainers: We support you to plan realistic, achievable goals and how to reach them. Working at your pace and on issues that matter to you, the results have been fantastic so far with over 90% of people achieving at least one of the goals in their action plan. Support is offered in the form of practical advice and information on the various services and support offered locally.  Healthy Communities Collaborative (cancer, Cardiovascular Disease, ): The service aims to promote earlier presentations of cancer/ cardiovascular disease in primary care, to facilitate earlier diagnosis and treatment. It does this by developing teams led by local people to identify and engage priority groups in their communities. They raise awareness, and educate people about recognising and presenting cancer symptoms/ cardiovascular disease. The work is done together with Cancer/ Cardiovascular networks and screening programmes, while supporting primary care in interpretation of best practice.  Time Banking : \"...time to give and take.\" Aims to strengthen communities by drawing people together and by developing mutual friendships and support. Time Banking is open to everyone, of any background, age or ability. Everyone has skills and experience to offer.',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,150,1,1,53.492903,-2.274601,'eng','2013-05-20 12:00:00','2013-05-20 12:00:00',NULL,NULL,'unlimited-potential'),(153,'Irlam Community Centre','Pat or Joan','Locklands Lane, off Ferry Hill Road','Irlam',NULL,'Salford','M44 6RB','0161 7762832','fsoadmin@scll.co.uk','http://www.salfordcommunityleisure.co.uk/lifestyles/locations/irlam-community-centre','Activities and groups include Zumba; Legs bums and tums; Line dancing (beginners welcome); Age 19+ yoga; Councillors surgery (second and fourth Tuesday of the month ); Tai Chi; Weight Watchers; A New You (free-run by Health Improvement Team); Monthly Quiz; Keep fit for over 50s (Thursday 1.30-2.30); Art class (Thursday 3-5pm); Red tiger karate club; Monthly Friday Luncheon club (for people living alone); Musical Theatre.',NULL,'Lifestyle_SC','https://www.facebook.com/pages/Salford-Community-Leisure/394597987283835',1,150,1,1,53.446817,-2.419114,'eng','2013-05-20 12:00:00','2013-05-20 12:00:00',NULL,NULL,'irlam-community-centre'),(154,'Rainbow Rooms Community Centre','Tracy or Sharon','259 Liverpool Road','Eccles',NULL,'Salford','M30 0QN','0161 7898091','fsoadmin@scll.co.uk','http://www.salfordcommunityleisure.co.uk/lifestyles/locations/rainbow-rooms-community-centre','Activities and groups include Wheelie Fit (Mon 11.30-12.30pm); Age Concern (Tues 9.30-12.30pm); Youth Workers; Zumba (Mon 8.30-9.15pm, Thurs 7.30-8.15pm, Fri 1.30-2.30pm); Over 50s; Mature Movers (Tues 10-12pm); Parkinson\'s Club (second Tuesday of the month); Over 60s social (Tues 1-3pm, Wed 1-3pm); Morris Dancing (Tues 5.30-10pm); Disability Drama (Wed 12.30-1.30pm, Thurs 12.30-1.30pm); Yoga (Wed 1.30-2.30pm); Karate; YANA (social group); Healthy Hips an